comments.body:
The possible situations here seem to be:

* Global ARG declared, never referenced => Warn unused;
* Global ARG declared without value, referenced => Warn no default;
* Global ARG declared with value, referenced => okay.

* New stage ARG declared, never referenced => Warn unused;
* New stage ARG declared without value, referenced => Warn no default;
* New stage ARG declared with value, referenced => Warn if global overridden (suggest moving to global)?

* Global ARG specified in stage, never referenced => Warn unused;
* Global ARG without value specified in stage, referenced => Warn no default;
* Global ARG with value specified in stage, referenced => Warn if global overridden?

... so a solution would be to:

* Issue a "declared ARG unused" warning for any stage, and Globally (if we have that level of introspection or post stage-processing reference-counting);
* Issue a "no default value in Dockerfile" warning Globally and for any stage;
* Consider issuing a "make ARG global" informational notice if a non-global ARG is referenced in a stage;
* Issue a "global ARG overridden" informational notice if a stage redefines a global ARG.

Does that logic make sense?  How's this sound as a solution?
